# 🌿 Contributing Guidelines

## Welcome, Contributors!

Thank you for your interest in contributing to this Tomato Leaf Disease Detection project! This repository contains both the deep learning model and the web application used to classify tomato leaf diseases using image inputs.

Your contributions—whether it's improving the model, enhancing the UI/UX of the web app, optimizing performance, or fixing bugs—are always welcome!

---

## 🧠 Project Credits

- **Model Developed by**: [Nuhan Gunasekara](https://www.linkedin.com/in/nuhangunasekara)  
- **Web Application Developed by**: [Hathik Ihthizam](https://www.linkedin.com/in/hathikihthizam/)

---

## 📏 Code Style

Please follow the existing code conventions used in the project:
- Python: Follow PEP8 guidelines.
- HTML/CSS/JS: Keep formatting consistent and modular.
- Maintain clear, meaningful variable and function names.
- Use consistent indentation (4 spaces in Python).

---

## 📚 Documentation

- Document all functions and classes using docstrings.
- Add inline comments where necessary to improve clarity.
- Update any relevant documentation if your contribution changes existing behavior or adds new features.

---

## 🧪 Testing

Before submitting a pull request:
- Thoroughly test your changes.
- Make sure all existing tests pass.
- If applicable, add test cases that cover your changes.

---

## 🐛 Issue Tracker

- Check the [Issues](../../issues) tab before starting work.
- If you pick an issue to work on, comment to let others know.
- You can also open a new issue if you find a bug or want to suggest a feature.

---

## 🔍 Code Review

- All pull requests will be reviewed by the maintainers.
- Be open to feedback—code reviews help us maintain high quality and long-term stability.
- You may be asked to make adjustments or clarify your implementation.

---

## ❓ Need Help?

If you need any clarifications about the model, app structure, or contribution flow, **feel free to ask** by opening an issue or reaching out via LinkedIn.

---

Thank you again for contributing and helping improve this project!
